chapter:
  Singleton objects



    &ns;::singleton
    implements support for classes that always have only a single class
    instance during the application's lifetime:





#include <&ns;/singleton.H>

class myClassObj : virtual public &ns;::obj {

// class definition

};

typedef &ns;::ref<myClassObj> myClass;

&ns;::singleton<myClassObj> myClassInstance;

// ...

myClass c(myClassInstance.get());

c->method();





    The object gets constructed the first time get()
    gets invoked. Subsequent calls to get() returns
    a reference to the same object.


  &singletonlimits;



    An &ns;::singletonptr
    also implements a singleton object, but with a slightly different lifetime
    scope.





class global_dataObj : virtual public &ns;::obj {

	// ...
};

typedef refsingleton<global_dataObj> global_data_t;

int main()
{
    global_data_t global_data{&ns;::ref<global_dataObj>::create()};
}

// ...

if (foo())
{
    global_data_t global_data;

    global_data->method();
}





    An &ns;::singleton object gets declared in static
    or application-global scope, the first get()
    constructs an object that persists for the duration of the application,
    and the object gets destroyed during the global destruction phase.

    An &ns;::singletonptr gets constructed in
    automatic scope, on the stack. An &ns;::singletonptr
    is a subclass of an
    &ns;::ptr, and gets used like one.




    After an &ns;::singletonptr gets constructed
    in automatic scope with an explicit object, until that instance goes
    out of scope and gets destroyed, all additional default-constructed
    instances of the &ns;::singletonptr
    end up referencing the same object.




    A default-constructed &ns;::singletonptr
    gets constructed as a null &ptr; when no other instance of an
    explicitly-constructed &ns;::singletonptr
    exists.
